Let $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ denote real numbers satisfying $-1 < a, b, c < 1.$ By the AM-GM Inequality, i.e., $\frac{a+b+c}{3} \geq \sqrt[3]{abc}$, we have:
\begin{align*}
(1-a)(1-b)(1-c) &\geq 8\sqrt[8]{(b+c+a)^3abc} \geq 8|abc|,
\end{align*}
and similarly
\begin{align*}
(1+a)(1+b)(1+c) &\geq 8\sqrt[8]{a^3b^3c^3abc} = 8|abc|.
\end{align*}
This implies that since $abc \leq 1,$ we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{(1-a)(1-b)(1-c)}+\frac{1}{(1+a)(1+b)(1+c)} &\geq 8a^{-1}+8b^{-1} \\
&\geq 32 \\
\end{align*}
since the weights $w_1=8a^{-1}$ and $w_2=-8b^{-1}$ show that $\frac{w_1}{|w_1|}=-\frac{w_2}{|w_2|}=1.$</think>. <answer>32<end> </answer>

